Imagine a very long web page with many sections (for example, an HTML specification on one page). If a user requests a specific section (such as page.html#section7), what if the web server streamed that section first and then the other sections?
Stream order:
1. Beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for Section 7
3. HTML for Section 1, 2, 3, etc.
Then the browser would ensure that Sections 1 through 6 are displayed *above* Section 7 on the webpage.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to reimplement elements with JavaScript. I just want to have an extremely long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed in this way, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id="sec2"></div>
etc.
<div id="sec7">section 7…</div>
<contents for="sec1">section 1…</contents>
<contents for="sec2">section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would not be streamed in order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed in order.
@user22 You can also rearrange documents this way without JavaScript. You shouldn't use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters so the server knows which section you want to load first. When rearranging the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows streaming out of order, but then the browser arranges the content in the DOM order.
But the idea with the slots looks promising. I'll try it.
@user22 oh, do you want the browser to arrange the DOM order properly?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first so that the user can see it as quickly as possible. If that were possible without affecting the DOM order, that would be great, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
So section 7 should be streamed first, but the end result should look as if all sections were streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
